digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    PiezoAccelerometer -> ChargeAmplifier;
    ChargeAmplifier -> HighPassFilter;
    HighPassFilter -> Amplifier;
    Amplifier -> AntiAliasingFilter;
    AntiAliasingFilter -> ADC;

    subgraph cluster_0 {
        label="Analog Front-End"
        PiezoAccelerometer;
        ChargeAmplifier;
        HighPassFilter;
        Amplifier;
        AntiAliasingFilter;
    }

    subgraph cluster_1 {
        label="Digital Processing"
        ADC;
    }
}
```

```Explanations
PiezoAccelerometer: This is the sensor that converts the mechanical vibration into an electrical charge. The accelerometer specified has a sensitivity of 100 pC/g, and the device will measure low-frequency vibrations up to 2 Hz with a peak amplification of 5 cm. The piezo element is assumed to have an adequate internal resistance and capacitance for the frequency of interest.

ChargeAmplifier: The charge amplifier is used to convert the charge output from the piezoelectric sensor into a usable voltage signal. It should be designed with a very high input impedance to avoid damping the sensor and with low bias current to minimize offset errors. The gain is set to provide the desired 1 V peak-to-peak output for the given peak charge generated by the accelerometer.

HighPassFilter: The high-pass filter serves to block DC and very low frequencies to satisfy the requirement of having a low-frequency response 3 dB down at 0.25 Hz. It also helps to eliminate any low-frequency noise and offsets from the system. 

Amplifier: This block provides additional amplification to ensure that the output signal reaches the desired level. Given that the output requirement is 1 V peak to peak, this stage will adjust the signal level accordingly. This amplifier should also maintain a low output impedance to drive any subsequent stages or loads.

AntiAliasingFilter: Prior to analog-to-digital conversion, an anti-aliasing filter is used to remove any frequency components above half the sampling rate (Nyquist frequency) to prevent aliasing. This filter needs to be a low-pass filter with a cutoff frequency set appropriately based on the ADC's sampling rate.

ADC: The analog-to-digital converter provides the means to digitize the conditioned analog signal for further digital processing, storage, or digital display. The sampling rate must be at least twice the highest frequency of interest (according to the Nyquist-Shannon sampling theorem).
```

